1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Here's a scenario.

2
00:00:07,300 --> 00:00:09,300
You're running a live keynote.

3
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:12,225
The speaker is thirty seconds from wrapping.

4
00:00:12,525 --> 00:00:14,775
You need to end this session,

5
00:00:15,075 --> 00:00:17,325
set the next one to ready,

6
00:00:17,625 --> 00:00:21,750
and trigger a broadcast — all in the next ninety seconds.

7
00:00:22,050 --> 00:00:25,800
The stage manager is on comms asking for a cue.

8
00:00:26,100 --> 00:00:30,600
The client is standing next to you asking how the schedule looks.

9
00:00:30,900 --> 00:00:34,650
You don't have time to move a mouse to the

10
00:00:34,950 --> 00:00:37,575
right place and click three different buttons.

11
00:00:37,875 --> 00:00:42,000
You need to work fast, with your eyes on the room.

12
00:00:42,300 --> 00:00:46,425
CueDeck has a full keyboard shortcut system built for exactly this.

13
00:00:46,725 --> 00:00:48,725
Let me show you everything.

14
00:00:49,025 --> 00:00:51,650
The `?` key opens the shortcut reference.

15
00:00:51,950 --> 00:00:54,575
You don't have to memorise anything —

16
00:00:54,875 --> 00:00:57,500
this panel is always one keypress away.

17
00:00:57,800 --> 00:01:00,050
On the left, the navigation shortcuts.

18
00:01:00,350 --> 00:01:02,975
On the right, help and general commands.

19
00:01:03,275 --> 00:01:06,275
Every shortcut in the app is listed here.

20
00:01:06,575 --> 00:01:10,700
Let me walk through the ones you'll actually use every day.

21
00:01:10,1000 --> 00:01:13,1000
The `/` key focuses the search bar instantly.

22
00:01:14,300 --> 00:01:16,550
Start typing a session name and

23
00:01:16,850 --> 00:01:20,600
the list filters in real time — no mouse required.

24
00:01:20,900 --> 00:01:22,900
`B` opens the broadcast bar.

25
00:01:23,200 --> 00:01:25,450
You can type a message and

26
00:01:25,750 --> 00:01:28,375
hit Enter without ever leaving the keyboard.

27
00:01:28,675 --> 00:01:31,300
`R` sets the selected session to READY.

28
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:35,350
One key, one action — as long as the session

29
00:01:35,650 --> 00:01:38,275
is in a state that allows it.

30
00:01:38,575 --> 00:01:41,950
`Escape` closes any open modal, dismisses the broadcast bar,

31
00:01:42,250 --> 00:01:45,250
clears the search — your universal exit key.

32
00:01:45,550 --> 00:01:48,550
And `Cmd+K` — or `Ctrl+K` on Windows —

33
00:01:48,850 --> 00:01:50,850
opens the command palette.

34
00:01:51,150 --> 00:01:53,400
That one gets its own section.

35
00:01:53,700 --> 00:01:57,825
Press `/` and the cursor jumps straight into the search field.

36
00:01:58,125 --> 00:02:01,875
I start typing 'workshop' and the session list filters immediately.

37
00:02:02,175 --> 00:02:04,175
Everything else disappears.

38
00:02:04,475 --> 00:02:07,100
I can see exactly what I need.

39
00:02:07,400 --> 00:02:11,900
Arrow key down to navigate, Escape to clear and get everything back.

40
00:02:12,200 --> 00:02:14,825
For a 30-session event with three rooms,

41
00:02:15,125 --> 00:02:18,875
this is how you find anything in under two seconds.

42
00:02:19,175 --> 00:02:22,925
Press `B` and the broadcast bar opens at the top

43
00:02:23,225 --> 00:02:25,850
of the screen — ready to type.

44
00:02:26,150 --> 00:02:29,900
I type my message — 'Sarah Chen please make your

45
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:33,575
way to the Main Stage' — and hit Enter.

46
00:02:33,875 --> 00:02:38,000
That message goes to every connected device in under a second.

47
00:02:38,300 --> 00:02:40,300
No menu.

48
00:02:40,600 --> 00:02:42,600
No clicking.

49
00:02:42,900 --> 00:02:44,900
Just `B`, type, Enter.

50
00:02:45,200 --> 00:02:48,950
The character counter updates as I type so I know

51
00:02:49,250 --> 00:02:52,250
I'm within the display limit for signage screens.

52
00:02:52,550 --> 00:02:54,800
And if I change my mind,

53
00:02:55,100 --> 00:02:57,725
`Escape` closes the bar without sending anything.

54
00:02:58,025 --> 00:03:00,275
This is the command palette, and

55
00:03:00,575 --> 00:03:04,325
it's the fastest way to do anything in CueDeck —

56
00:03:04,625 --> 00:03:07,625
especially if you already know what you want.

57
00:03:07,925 --> 00:03:10,175
It searches across two things simultaneously:

58
00:03:10,475 --> 00:03:13,850
your live sessions, and a set of static commands.

59
00:03:14,150 --> 00:03:16,775
Start typing and it fuzzy-matches against both.

60
00:03:17,075 --> 00:03:20,450
Type 'keyn' and I get the two keynote sessions.

61
00:03:20,750 --> 00:03:24,125
I can navigate the list with the up and

62
00:03:24,425 --> 00:03:27,050
down arrows — watch the highlight move.

63
00:03:27,350 --> 00:03:30,350
Press Enter and I jump straight to that

64
00:03:30,650 --> 00:03:32,650
session in the list.

65
00:03:32,950 --> 00:03:35,575
The context panel opens on the right,

66
00:03:35,875 --> 00:03:38,125
ready for me to take action.

67
00:03:38,425 --> 00:03:42,175
Type 'go live' and the static 'Go Live' command appears

68
00:03:42,475 --> 00:03:46,225
— pressing Enter on that triggers the Go Live action

69
00:03:46,525 --> 00:03:48,525
on the currently selected session.

70
00:03:48,825 --> 00:03:50,825
No clicking required.

71
00:03:51,125 --> 00:03:54,500
The palette closes the moment I confirm an action.

72
00:03:54,800 --> 00:03:58,175
`Escape` at any point closes it without doing anything.

73
00:03:58,475 --> 00:04:00,725
The keyboard navigation is fully consistent:

74
00:04:01,025 --> 00:04:04,025
up and down arrows to move through results,

75
00:04:04,325 --> 00:04:06,575
Enter to confirm, Escape to exit.

76
00:04:06,875 --> 00:04:10,625
Once you know those three keys you can use the

77
00:04:10,925 --> 00:04:13,175
palette entirely without touching the mouse.

78
00:04:13,475 --> 00:04:16,475
The `R` shortcut is a single-key action —

79
00:04:16,775 --> 00:04:19,775
it sets the selected session to READY immediately,

80
00:04:20,075 --> 00:04:22,075
without opening any modal.

81
00:04:22,375 --> 00:04:26,125
This is the shortcut that gets used more than any

82
00:04:26,425 --> 00:04:28,425
other in a live run.

83
00:04:28,725 --> 00:04:32,475
You've just ended a session, you select the next one

84
00:04:32,775 --> 00:04:35,025
in the list, you hit `R`.

85
00:04:35,325 --> 00:04:38,325
The stage manager gets the READY signal instantly.

86
00:04:38,625 --> 00:04:40,875
Then you pick up your radio.

87
00:04:41,175 --> 00:04:43,425
Three keypresses to advance the programme:

88
00:04:43,725 --> 00:04:45,975
click the next session, `R`, done.

89
00:04:46,275 --> 00:04:48,900
Or if you're on the command palette,

90
00:04:49,200 --> 00:04:51,450
you don't even need the click.

91
00:04:51,750 --> 00:04:56,250
Let me run through a realistic sequence using nothing but the keyboard.

92
00:04:56,550 --> 00:04:58,550
Watch.

93
00:04:58,850 --> 00:05:02,600
End the current session — I'll use the command palette.

94
00:05:02,900 --> 00:05:05,525
`Cmd+K`, type 'end', select End Session, Enter.

95
00:05:05,825 --> 00:05:07,825
Session 1 is now ENDED.

96
00:05:08,125 --> 00:05:11,875
Select session 2 — arrow key down in the session

97
00:05:12,175 --> 00:05:14,175
list, Enter to open it.

98
00:05:14,475 --> 00:05:17,475
Hit `R` — session 2 is now READY.

99
00:05:17,775 --> 00:05:20,025
Broadcast the speaker call — `B`,

100
00:05:20,325 --> 00:05:23,325
type 'Marco Rossi to the stage please', Enter.

101
00:05:23,625 --> 00:05:25,625
Done.

102
00:05:25,925 --> 00:05:30,800
Check the schedule — `/`, type the next session name, Escape to return.

103
00:05:31,100 --> 00:05:33,100
Entire sequence.

104
00:05:33,400 --> 00:05:35,400
No mouse.

105
00:05:35,700 --> 00:05:37,700
Twelve keypresses.

106
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:41,000
In a high-pressure moment on a live stage,

107
00:05:41,300 --> 00:05:43,300
that speed is real.

108
00:05:43,600 --> 00:05:48,475
It's the difference between keeping up with the show and falling behind it.

109
00:05:48,775 --> 00:05:52,900
Keyboard shortcuts and the command palette are the production professional's interface.

110
00:05:53,200 --> 00:05:56,950
They reward the operators who invest ten minutes learning them

111
00:05:57,250 --> 00:06:00,625
with a measurably faster, smoother, less error-prone show day.

112
00:06:00,925 --> 00:06:03,925
The full reference is always one `?` away.

113
00:06:04,225 --> 00:06:07,225
Start with the four essentials: `?` for help,

114
00:06:07,525 --> 00:06:09,775
`B` for broadcast, `/` for search,

115
00:06:10,075 --> 00:06:12,075
`Cmd+K` for everything else.

116
00:06:12,375 --> 00:06:14,375
The rest will come naturally.

117
00:06:14,675 --> 00:06:17,300
Next episode: CueDeck on mobile and tablet.

118
00:06:17,600 --> 00:06:21,350
How the layout adapts, practical setups for stage managers on

119
00:06:21,650 --> 00:06:24,275
an iPad and registration on a phone,

120
00:06:24,575 --> 00:06:28,325
and what you need to know about running realtime production

121
00:06:28,625 --> 00:06:30,625
on a handheld device.

122
00:06:30,925 --> 00:06:32,925
I'll see you there.
